{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22341652-3445-4cd1-aaff-abe591fa04ce","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug — it means your code is dereferencing a null object reference. This is **not a CLR activation issue**.\n\n**CLR activation logs** diagnose problems like:\n- The wrong .NET runtime version being loaded\n- Runtime failing to load at all\n- Unexpected Feature-on-Demand dialogs\n\nThey won't help with a `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**To find your bug, I'd recommend:**\n1. Check the **stack trace** from the exception — it shows exactly which line has the null reference.\n2. Use a debugger or add logging around that code path.\n3. Share the stack trace or crash dump here and I can help pinpoint it.\n\nDo you have a stack trace, crash dump, or source code you'd like me to look at?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d786afe5-d7ad-47f5-a2a3-bed1ae8dd31c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about which runtime version gets loaded by the shim (mscoree.dll) — things like picking the wrong runtime, failing to load a runtime, Feature-on-Demand dialogs, etc. A NullReferenceException is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation/loading problem.\n\n\nI'll explain to the user why this skill isn't the right fit for their issue.","outputTokens":407,"requestId":"7841:2671F1:3E760E:4880B2:69FA9AF4"},"id":"c66c4f44-ea86-4152-a874-21ed8e52af41","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:35:58.874Z","parentId":"847c6c4c-77f1-4e72-ac40-012cbbd9f708"}
